    "summary": "The Tet Offensive, launched on January 30, 1968, was a coordinated surprise attack by North Vietnamese and Viet Cong forces on over 100 South Vietnamese cities and towns during the Vietnamese New Year truce period. Named for the Tết Nguyên Đán lunar new year holiday, the offensive included simultaneous attacks on the American embassy compound in Saigon, the ancient imperial city of Hue, and dozens of provincial capitals. While a military failure — American and South Vietnamese forces repelled the attacks and inflicted enormous casualties on the attackers — the offensive had a decisive psychological and political impact.\n\nThe scale and audacity of the attacks contradicted official American statements that the [[event:2674|Vietnam War]] was being won and that enemy forces were nearing collapse. Television news coverage brought the fighting directly into American living rooms, including the image of Saigon's police chief executing a Viet Cong prisoner in the street. Walter Cronkite, the most trusted news anchor in America, declared that the United States was mired in stalemate. President Johnson, facing collapsing public support, announced he would not seek reelection.\n\nThe Tet Offensive is widely regarded as the turning point of the Vietnam War, not militarily but politically. It demonstrated the gap between official optimism and ground reality, accelerated the growth of the antiwar movement, and set the United States on the path to disengagement from Vietnam.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tet_Offensive",
